snippet.textDisplay:
Clutching at straws here. They claim his visa cancellation is Illogical, irrational and unreasonable, but that’s neither here nor there. 
Did he make false declarations on his visa application? Yes
Has he breached COVID quarantine previously while knowing he tested positive? Yes
Did he have a medical exemption to enter Australia? No. (The Australian Visa website clearly states that testing positive and recovering from COVID does not constitute a medical exemption for vaccination. Other countries, such as Germany, do allow it, but Australia does not).  
Tennis Australia does NOT grant visa, so they can only tell him he can play, not that he can enter Australia.
The judge who oversaw his original case to have his first visa cancellation reversed stated publicly that he was very much against the governments decision to deport him… he said this before the case was even presented to him in court. It was just his personal opinion on the case before the case happened and any evidence was presented to him. If even a juror had stated that they had a strong sentiment one way or the other before a case was held they would be struck off the jury, so to allow a judge to sit before a case when they have publicly stated that they have already made up their mind is absurd.
